                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17220404-32-off168 t17220404-32-cd169"></join> last, of which he languished till the 21st, of the said Month, and then Dy'd
            </rs>. He was a second time indicted on the Coroners Inquisition for the said Murder. The Evidence for the King depos'd, that the Deceased, the prisoner, and others being at <placeName id="t17220404-32-crimeloc170">the Rose and Crown in Shoo Lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17220404-32-crimeloc170" type="placeName" value="the Rose and Crown in Shoo Lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17220404-32-crimeloc170" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17220404-32-off168 t17220404-32-crimeloc170"></join>, the prisoner strok'd the Deceased over the Head, and provok'd him to fight; that they fought together; that the People endeavour'd to part them but the prisoner would fight on; that the Deceased said he had enough, but the prisoner struck him several times afterwards on the Breast and Head, that the Deceased on his Death Bed declar'd, Carter had kill'd him. The Surgeons depos'd, that the Hurts were not mortal, unless by throwing him into a Fever, which night be caus'd by hard Drinking. The prisoner in his defence called 
